Here's a sample source code for Project 1, which is a basic calculator that supports addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division operations:

```
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Calculator {

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
		System.out.print("Enter first number: ");
		int num1 = scanner.nextInt();
		System.out.print("Enter second number: ");
		int num2 = scanner.nextInt();

		System.out.println("Choose an operation (+ - * /): ");
		String operation = scanner.next();

		switch(operation) {
			case "+":
				System.out.println("Result: " + (num1 + num2));
				break;
			case "-":
				System.out.println("Result: " + (num1 - num2));
				break;
			case "*":
				System.out.println("Result: " + (num1 * num2));
				break;
			case "/":
				if(num2 == 0) {
					System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero!");
				} else {
					System.out.println("Result: " + (num1 / num2));
				}
				break;
			default:
				System.out.println("Invalid operation!");
		}

		scanner.close();
	}

}
```

This code prompts the user to enter two numbers and choose an operation to perform. The input is then processed and the result is displayed on the console. The code also handles the special case of division by zero using exception handling techniques.

Here's a sample source code for Project 2, which is a student grading system:

```
import java.util.Scanner;

public class StudentGradingSystem {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
		System.out.println("Welcome to the Student Grading System");
		System.out.println("Enter the number of students:");
		int numberOfStudents = scanner.nextInt();

		Student[] students = new Student[numberOfStudents];

		for(int i = 0; i < numberOfStudents; i++) {
			System.out.println("Enter name of student " + (i+1) + ":");
			String name = scanner.next();
			scanner.nextLine();
			System.out.println("Enter grade for " + name + ": ");
			double grade = scanner.nextDouble();
			students[i] = new Student(name, grade);
		}

		for(int i = 0; i < numberOfStudents; i++) {
			System.out.println(students[i].getName() + ": " + students[i].getGrade());
		}

		scanner.close();
	}
}

class Student {
	private String name;
	private double grade;

	public Student(String name, double grade) {
		this.name = name;
		this.grade = grade;
	}

	public String getName() {
		return name;
	}

	public double getGrade() {
		return grade;
	}
}
```

This code prompts the user to enter the number of students and their grades. It then stores the student details in an array of Student objects and displays the results on the console. The Student class encapsulates the name and grade fields, and provides getter methods to access these fields. The code demonstrates the use of objects, arrays, encapsulation, and basic input and output operations in Java.
